               <item n="project_comment_old">&lt;p&gt;[[Broomhead I]] has notes on p. 230 and translates on pp. 229-230: &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a1 She looked at the novice. He glowed as if with fire &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a2 [He] went. [He] stood in front of her as if [he would like] to drink this lotus-shaped one (f.). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a3 that: But however this patient and indestructible one was fettered. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a4 ... the seed of sorrows is the evil of the world. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;a5 The superiority of the Omniscient in no other way. The śīla &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b1 This [is] non-vessel here. 19. ... a relic-filled stūpa &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b2 The sorrows of [the beings]. Therefore [it is] not thy duty to (remove) passion(s). &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b3 It began to prick her. She, having fallen into confusion, said to him. ['it' probably refers to 'passion'] &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b4 At this time he thought: 'In order to escape from this great difficulty I ...' &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;b5 He who with this difficult purchase-price of lives ... the great (king?) &lt;/p&gt;</item>
